    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-06-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-06-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="1420"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1420">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.52/320.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Consul <persName type="from">Miller</persName> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Tampico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-06-10">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 10, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Department’s June 8, relative request of Spanish Ambassador in regard reported
                    forced loan of 500,000 pesos; following reply has been received from General
                    Caballeros: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>This Government has not imposed upon residing Spaniards payment forced
                            loan of 500,000 pesos or any other loan and has not even exacted war
                            contributions from them. It is therefore very strange 1 at said
                            foreigners should complain of prejudices or damage which they have not
                            sustained nor are threatened with, and it is also very strange that said
                            subjects of a nation which has recognized the Huerta Government should
                            solicit of the Department of State of your country seeking its good
                            service in defence of what they pretend to make believe are Spanish
                            interests. Steps are being taken to require Spanish residents in Tampico
                            to state to this Government from what source or authority they have
                            received impositions of forced loan of which complaint is made.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Miller</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
